It’s officially Crohn’s and Colitis Awareness Week!! Help me make #ibdvisible and spread the word! 💜 
-
- Please share this with family and friends!! 
- 
It took me years to get diagnosed with Crohn’s. I had gotten misdiagnosed and my symptoms became really bad during a flare up. So bad to the point I had to spend an entire month in a hospital with no foods or liquids and everything being fed through an IV. They later drain an abscess I had that was the size of a softball in my hip and did a bowl resection surgery. After all of this happening we found a medication that worked for me and I began to recover. This situation occurred when I was only 14 years old. Help me make IBD, Crohn’s and Colitis visible so we can avoid situations like this in the future for other people!! 💜

#ccawarenessweek #ibdvisible #crohnsdisease #crohns #ibd #ibdwarrior #crohnswarrior #crohnsandcolitis #crohnsandcolitisawarenessweek #crohnsandcolitisfoundation #mystory #guthealth

During this time I was 14 years old and going through a lot but I always stayed positive for my family, doctors and I. There wasn’t many people that knew what was going on besides close friends, family, and agents. I was at an unhealthy weight of 80 pounds at 5’8. It was difficult for me to put on weight because my food couldn’t process normally during a Crohn’s flare up. I’m not posting this to ask for pity but to raise awareness for IBD, Crohn’s & Colitis. The more people know, the less difficult it has to be for others. Please share this and help me raise awareness!! 

I also wanted to give a special thanks to anyone that helped me during this time.. friends, family, agents, doctors, nurses, emotional support animals, volunteers at the hospitals, etc.

It’s world IBD Day!!! 🌎💜(Please read below) 

More than 10 million people around the world live with Crohn’s disease and Ulcerative colitis, also known as IBD. I wanted to share these photos with you to show how quickly and intensely your life can be changed by Crohn’s disease. You can be strong and active but once a flare up hits, you can start to lose unhealthy amounts of weight, need to go through multiple blood tests and scans, colonoscopies and endoscopies, new medications, develop abscesses that can make it hard to move or stretch the body, and so much more. After going through all of that, I was lucky enough to go back into remission and be healthy again on a new medication. 

I never share my stories with Crohn’s for pity but to spread awareness of what it’s like to live with an autoimmune disease at a young age. If my story can help even one person.. I’m happy to share it, even if it is a difficult subject for me to speak on at times. 

So today, I encourage you to please DONATE to the @crohnscolitisfoundationla_oc fundraiser link in my bio. If you’re in LA or can be in LA June 11th, please join me in the Crohn’s and Colitis Walk this year by signing up with the donation link in my bio. If you’re unable to join, please help share my story and encourage other people to donate and join. This means so much to me, more than I can even explain.. thank you. 💜🌎
